@christiansandberg do you know what happens when calling `stop()` to a non-started, or already stopped task? I know with socketcan we would send another `TX_DELETE` to the kernel's bcm interface. 

Assuming that is okay I'd say we go with your idea @felixdivo. The `Bus.send_periodic` [api](https://github.com/hardbyte/python-can/blob/develop/can/bus.py#L175) is changed to keep a reference to the task in the bus instance and in [`Bus.shutdown`](https://github.com/hardbyte/python-can/blob/develop/can/bus.py#L279) we call `stop()` on all the (running/remaining) tasks.

I know python-can often gets used in tools which run for days/months so we don't really want to keep all periodic tasks around if they have been manually stopped. Storing a Weak Reference in the `Bus` won't help us because then we don't get the benefit of keeping the task alive while the `Bus` is there. I guess we can hijak the `Task.stop()` or `Task.__del__` method to remove itself from the `Bus` (note there are restartable tasks...) but I'm open to any better ideas?

