@jonturneratduke - Looks like we have some roadblock with the API here. Before the client can upload an individual chunk, it must contact the data service API to get a [pre-signed URL](https://github.com/Duke-Translational-Bioinformatics/duke-data-service/blob/f134b7f05feced88f75a96bf0523822aff16a837/app/models/chunk.rb#L44) for that chunk. This URL is signed with an [expiration date](https://github.com/Duke-Translational-Bioinformatics/duke-data-service/blob/f134b7f05feced88f75a96bf0523822aff16a837/app/models/storage_provider.rb#L56), and assuming that expiration date is honored by the object store, it will cause a problem:

If a chunk fails and we want to retry it in the future, we'd need to handle the case where the expiration date has passed. It looks like the URLs are valid for 5 minutes, so this will be very common. The options there would be to:

1. Generate a new chunk object. The new chunk would have a new expiration date, but this method is problematic because the old chunk still exists in the database as part of the upload object (and we have no mechanism to delete it). @johnbradley was able to generate multiple chunks with the same [number](https://github.com/Duke-Translational-Bioinformatics/duke-data-service/blob/f134b7f05feced88f75a96bf0523822aff16a837/app/models/chunk.rb#L13). These duplicate-numbered chunks are included in the [manifest](https://github.com/Duke-Translational-Bioinformatics/duke-data-service/blob/f134b7f05feced88f75a96bf0523822aff16a837/app/models/upload.rb#L36) when [completing](https://github.com/Duke-Translational-Bioinformatics/duke-data-service/blob/f134b7f05feced88f75a96bf0523822aff16a837/app/models/upload.rb#L46) the upload, so would lead to corrupted data when combining the chunks.
2. Refresh the expiration date on the existing chunk. This is not implemented at the API level, but changing the [updated_at](https://github.com/Duke-Translational-Bioinformatics/duke-data-service/blob/f134b7f05feced88f75a96bf0523822aff16a837/app/models/chunk.rb#L41) time on the chunk object would result in a refreshed URL.
3. Abandon the entire upload and start over.

@johnbradley is testing more on 1., to see what happens upon completion

